# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-hall-and-sons
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] The company was established in 1971 as A&P-Appledore International Ltd (APA), a joint venture technology transfer consultancy between British shipbuilding companies Austin & Pickersgill and Appledore Shipbuilders, and focused on ship design and construction.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] Initially the business was directed towards the growing Far East market, as well as the Americas and Europe.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] Based on the production engineering solutions developed for the innovative 'ship factory' at Appledore in the late 1960s, and subsequently at Pallion, Sunderland, APA developed the formal Build Strategy approach.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] This was taken up by Hyundai when they developed the first modern shipyard in South Korea at Ulsan in the 1970s.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] The Build Strategy template was subsequently adopted in British Shipbuilders' other shipyards, and in the USA.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] Following sale of Appledore Shipbuilders to the Government at the time of the collapse of its parent Court Line in 1974, and the subsequent nationalisation of Austin & Pickersgill in 1977, the shareholding of APA was purchased by its management.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] APA acquired the shiprepair facilities of Falmouth Docks & Engineering Company in 1984 and they remain one of the company's two major centres.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] The Company subsequently focused on shiprepairs rather than shipbuilding, becoming A&P Group in 1995 and being acquired by Royal Bank Development Capital in 1997.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] Over the years the company has operated shiprepair facilities in many parts of the world.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] From the mid-1970s until privatisation in 1994, the Neorion shiprepair yard on Syros was managed for the Greek Government.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] Dubai Drydocks opened in 1983 under APA management.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] The takeover of the former naval dockyard at Gibraltar as "Gibrepair" in 1985 was short-lived, a victim of local social politics.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] In 2001 the A&P acquired Cammell Laird's shipyards at Birkenhead, Teesside and Tyneside.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] In 2005 A&P sold the Birkenhead yard to Northwestern Shiprepairers & Shipbuilders and closed its facilities in Southampton (King George V Dock) and the four-dock complex in Wallsend, near Newcastle upon Tyne, in order to focus all ship repair activity in its newer facilities in Hebburn (A&P Tyne).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] A&P Tees at Middlesbrough was retained to support the important Southern North Sea offshore oil and gas operations and dredging contractors; the strategically situated Falmouth operation (A&P Falmouth) was also retained.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] In 2009 A&P was fully acquired by Cardiff property developer Bailey Group; that company had previously acquired a 50% stake in 2006.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] In 2011 A&P Group was acquired by Atlantic & Peninsula Marine Services, which also has an interest in Cammell Laird.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] A&P Tyne is located at Hebburn on the River Tyne, Tyne and Wear.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] The facility consists of two dry docks (only one is currently in use), two quays and a large steel fabrication shed.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] The facility also has eight cranes lifting up to 100 tonnes, a steel workshop, joinery workshop and engineering workshop.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] The dry dock at A&P Tyne is the largest on the east coast of the UK.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] It is 259 metres (850 ft) long, 45.7 metres (150 ft) wide and has a depth of 5.6 metres (18 ft) below the datum of navigational charts allowing it to accommodate a wide variety of ships.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] The two quays are Bede Quay and West Quay.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] A&P Tees was located in Middlesbrough, on the River Tees.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] The yard had two dry docks and six cranes ranging up to forty tonnes lifting capacity.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] Dry dock number one was 175.4 metres (575 ft) long, 23.4 metres (77 ft) wide and had a depth of 1.7 metres (5 ft 7 in) below chart datum.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] Dry dock number two was 120 metres (390 ft) long, 18.6 metres (61 ft) wide and a had a depth below chart datum of 0.37 metres (1 ft 3 in).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] Like A&P Tyne, A&P Tees had a wide variety of workshops and fabrication sheds around the site.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] In mid-2024 A&P Group ceased operations at its Tees facility in a strategic move to consolidate its North East operations into its more extensive facility in Hebburn.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] A&P Falmouth is located in Falmouth, Cornwall.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] The yard is located in the third largest natural deep water harbour in the world, and is the largest ship repair complex in the UK.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] A&P Falmouth has three large graving docks and can accommodate ships up to 100,000 DWT.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] Number two dock (Queen Elizabeth Dock) is the largest graving dock and is 252.8 metres (829 ft) long, 39.6 metres (130 ft) wide and a has depth below chart datum of 5.6 metres (18 ft).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] Dock number three is 220.98 metres (725 ft) long, 28.04 metres (92 ft) wide and a depth below chart datum of 3.2 metres (10 ft).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] Dock number four is 172.5 metres (566 ft) long, 26.21 metres (86 ft) wide and has a depth below chart datum of 2.9 metres (9 ft 6 in).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] There are four wharfs in the yard: County Wharf, Duchy Wharf, Queens Wharf and "South of Queens Wharf".
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] The yard has six cranes, with a total load capacity of 60 tonnes.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/a-p-group] It has also a steel fabrication shed, engineering workshop, electrical workshop and joinery workshop.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The word "clipper" was first used for sailing vessels in the United States and argument arose in the 20th century about whether *Scottish Maid'*s underlying design had been copied from America, and whether she should properly have been called a clipper at all.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] It now seems agreed that "clipper" is best regarded as simply a name for a fast merchant sailing vessel and the particular design was arrived at independently on the two sides of the Atlantic.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Much of *Scottish Maid'*s career was transporting passengers and goods between Aberdeen and London.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] She was lost in a storm off the Farne Islands in 1888; the crew escaped by lifeboat.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] From the beginning of the nineteenth century the word "clipper" started to be used in Britain for a fast sailing ship.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Also, at this time the Aberdeen shipbuilding industry started to expand considerably.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Communication with London was via the North Sea along Britain's east coast.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Aberdeen's first steam ship, *Queen of Scotland*, a paddle steamer with a wooden hull, was built by John Duffus and Co. in 1829 and there followed a succession of similar vessels.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Aberdeen's first iron ship was the *John Garrow* launched in 1837.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The most prominent of Aberdeen's six shipyards, that of Alexander Hall and Sons, had been established in 1790 – between 1811 and 1877 they built 290 vessels with tonnages from 20 to 2,600 tons.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] In 1836 a new law was introduced in Britain for measuring the load carrying capacity (registered tonnage) of a ship.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The officially measured tonnage was particularly important for ships trading on short routes and making frequent use of harbours because charges for employing a maritime pilot, entering ports and for docking depended on tonnage.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The "new measurement" of a ship's gross register tonnage involved estimating the internal cross-sectional area averaged over several places along the hull and multiplying this by the overall internal length.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The length was measured at a height of half-depth at the midship position.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Hall's designers realised that by having the bow and stern, angled away from vertical when above half-depth, the measured tonnage would be less for a greater load carrying capacity.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Increasing the length would, by itself, have increased the tonnage.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] However, it also spread farther apart the positions at which the cross-sectional areas were to be measured so, if the vessel had pointed ends, the outermost areas would become smaller and so the average area would also be reduced.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The Halls correctly calculated this would *reduce* the tonnage even if the vessel was longer and could carry more goods.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] They also anticipated that a pointed bow with a highly raked stem would improve the speed of the vessel.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] For the reasons given above, the 1836 change in tonnage law advantaged vessels that were larger at points above half-depth and also that were pointed at the bow (and stern) even if the pointed shape made the vessel artificially longer.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] *Scottish Maid* was the first to have been deliberately designed to take advantage of the new law and was early in Britain to have a markedly pointed bow with the wooden beam at the very front angled forward sharply.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] This gave what at the time was a very striking appearance.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Anxious that such a radical design would not be approved by the purchasers, Halls shipyard built the new vessel starting from the stern and then constructed a temporary "skeleton" bow at the front to gain Aberdeen Line's approval.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Once completed and launched, the *Scottish Maid* exceeded expectations.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] In America some vessels, particularly the Baltimore clippers, had been called clippers for some time – *Scottish Maid* and her sister vessels also started to become known under this name which became associated with their particular shape of hull.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] *Scottish Maid'*s "clipper bow", later also to be called the "Aberdeen bow", was designed to make the vessel fast and maneuverable.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Scale models were tested in a water tank.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] A pointed bow was selected for the hull with the stem sharply raked forward (at some 50° from vertical) and the sternpost and masts raked aft.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Then a mock-up was fitted to a conventional hull to demonstrate to the owners the intended design.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Not only was the bow raked forward but the planking of the hull went over the stem, right to the front of the bow so the vessel cut the water cleanly.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The bowsprit was kept low to leave room for larger headsails.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The bow-lines were straight although below the waterline they were slightly hollow.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The vessel proved to be very fast, travelling between Aberdeen and London (500 miles (800 km)) in 49 hours at an average speed of about 9 knots and competing well against steam driven paddle steamers so in 1842 Hall's built three sister ships of the same design.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] In February 1854 *Scottish Maid* carried emigrant passengers to Australia who wrote to the press praising the attention and kindness given to them by the captain.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] In 1853 the collectors of excise brought a case against the ship's master, Arthur Sinclair, who had only declared one gallon of whisky but over three gallons were found on board.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The case was dismissed after Sinclair said that he knew nothing of the extra spirit.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] In 1862 one of the crew fell overboard and was drowned while the vessel was in tow down the River Tyne at Jarrow.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] When in passage from Stettin to Newcastle in 1867 she met drift ice and was forced ashore at Kronborg.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] She was helped off and towed in to Elsinore.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] In 1884 the vessel was underway to Sunderland when she got caught in a severe storm that sank several other vessels.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] *Scottish Maid* was blown past her destination but was able to anchor in Bridlington Bay from where she was towed in to Bridlington.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] She made her own way back to Sunderland but from there had to be towed back to Aberdeen for major repairs because her topmasts and rigging had been destroyed.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] After the crew had tried for nearly seven hours to pump out the incoming seawater they had to abandon ship as *Scottish Maid* sank and was totally wrecked.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The six crew were able to reach shore safely near Seahouses using their lifeboat.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] In the earliest decades of the 19th century the route between London and Leith, Edinburgh's port on Scotland's east coast, was served by single-masted cutter-rigged smacks with a large and unmanageable mainsail so that a crew of 14 might be required.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The 460-mile (740 km) voyage, for passengers, mail and cargo, took 50 hours at the very best (about 8 knots, somewhat faster than the more expensive stagecoach), 5–6 days for a swift passage, and several weeks in adverse conditions.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] There was no railway linking the cities.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] By 1830 two-masted schooners were beginning to be used and their more efficient sail plan involving both square and fore-and-aft sails reduced the time for the passage and made it somewhat more predictable.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The broad, short shape of the hulls of these vessels was required by a 1784 anti-smuggling law that required that the length of a vessel (excluding square-rigged) should be no more than 3.5 times longer than its beam.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] In 1836 the law was changed to make it possible to have narrower ships so vessels intended to be fast could take advantage of this.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] In 1839 some Aberdeen ship owners, aware of the upcoming competition from the Aberdeen and London Steam Navigation Company, approached Hall's shipyard for a fast schooner and orders for the other three sister vessels followed *Scottish Maid*s success.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The design of the bow was credited for the improved speed and by 1848 thirty-six similar vessels had been built, twenty-seven of them schooners.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] After 1845 Hall's were receiving orders from London and Liverpool and ships from other countries were being built to similar designs.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Aberdeen's first transoceanic tea clippers, built in 1846, did not show a particular turn of speed because the "Aberdeen bow" was less well suited to larger full-rigged ships.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Nonetheless, for smaller vessels the Aberdeen bow became well known in shipbuilding circles and the ships became called "clippers" Hall's clipper ship *Stornoway*, built in 1850, soon became known as a "China clipper".
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The Aberdeen-built *Thermopylae* of 1868 was to compete with *Cutty Sark* (1869) but 1869 was the year of the last clipper, *Caliph*, to be built in Aberdeen because the opening of the Suez Canal made them obsolescent.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] In the academic journal *Mariner's Mirror* of 1943, Boyd Cable published "The World's First Clipper" which awarded the accolade to *Scottish Maid*.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Despite the title the article starts with a lengthy appreciation, almost a eulogy, of Alexander Hall who started life as a farm worker in Auchterless in remote, rural Aberdeenshire and went on to establish and run Aberdeen's pre-eminent shipyard Alexander Hall and Sons which built *Scottish Maid*.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] His requisite design, a pointed bow with concave bow-lines and a stem angled steeply forward, started, in his estimation, with the *Scottish Maid* of 1839 and was followed in America by the *Rainbow* in 1845.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] The later larger clippers, now sometimes called extreme clippers, for structural reasons could not have a highly raked stem and these vessels were first built in the United States.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Anderson responded in 1945 with "Hollow Bows and 'First Clippers'" citing a well-made professional model in a Swedish museum of an English three-decker of 1665–1670 with a bow below the waterline more hollow than *Rainbow*.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] In 1946 William Salisbury wrote in "Hollow Water-Lines and Early Clippers" that *Scottish Maid* was simply one of the earlier clippers and much more research was needed in Britain to decide what interaction there was (if any) between American and British designs.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] J.Henderson reported he had inspected an original model at Hall's shipyard of a vessel with a greater stem rake than the *Scottish Maid* and its bow-lines were straight, not concave or convex.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] In 1948 Howard Chapelle wrote of the claims in Boyd Cable's article "It is my opinion that these claims are wholly untenable and are to be accounted for only because Mr Cable did not know of the extensive American literature relating to the subject of clippers".
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] Chapelle wrote that "clipper" had simply become a name for a fast sailing ship and that any discussion was useless unless it was with reference to a particular type of vessel.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-bow] In 1973 MacGregor agreed with this opinion and wrote that, by any reasonable definition of clipper, *Scottish Maid* was not the first in Britain and doubted whether it was even the first in Aberdeen.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The council has been under no overall control since 2002.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Since 2022 it has been led by a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrat coalition.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] It meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices at the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a royal burgh by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Elections for the council were only introduced in 1833.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to that the council was not an elected body; when vacancies arose the existing council appointed successors.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was historically part of Aberdeenshire, but the functions affecting the burgh which operated at county level were relatively few, largely being limited to judicial functions and lieutenancy.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] When elected county councils were created in 1890 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1889, Aberdeen Corporation was deemed capable of running county-level local government functions, and so the burgh was excluded from the area administered by Aberdeenshire County Council.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] In 1891 Aberdeen's boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the River Dee.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The historic county boundary between Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire in this area followed the River Dee.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Following the absorption of Torry on the south bank of the river in 1891, the city straddled the two counties.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899, removing the city from the two counties for lieutenancy and other purposes as well as local government functions.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The city boundaries were subsequently enlarged several times, gaining further territory from both Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire, notably in 1935, 1952 and 1970.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Local government across Scotland was reorganised in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973, which replaced the counties, burghs and landward districts with a two-tier system of regions and districts.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] One of the districts was called 'City of Aberdeen', which formed part of Grampian Region.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] City of Aberdeen District Council was therefore a lower-tier district authority, with upper-tier regional functions being provided by Grampian Regional Council.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The City of Aberdeen district covered a larger area than the pre-1975 city, taking in the parishes of Dyce, Newhills, Old Machar, and Peterculter from Aberdeenshire and Nigg from Kincardineshire.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] All except Dyce had previously ceded territory to the city in pre-1975 boundary changes.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Nigg added in 1975 just covered the residual rural parts of the old parish around Cove Bay; Nigg village itself had been absorbed into the city in 1935.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Old Machar was named after St Machar's Cathedral in Old Aberdeen, which had been absorbed into the city in 1891; the parish of Old Machar that was absorbed in 1975 was just the residual part of the cathedral's old parish which lay north of the River Don, including Bridge of Don.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Local government was reorganised again in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] (Scotland) Act 1994, which abolished the regions and districts created in 1975 and established 32 single-tier council areas across Scotland.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The existing City of Aberdeen District became one of the new council areas.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The 1994 Act named the new council area 'City of Aberdeen', but this was changed to 'Aberdeen City' by a council resolution on 9 May 1995, before the new council area came into force, allowing the new council to take the name 'Aberdeen City Council'.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Following the 2022 election a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrats coalition took control of the council.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The first election to the City of Aberdeen District Council was held in 1974, initially operating as a shadow authority alongside the outgoing authorities until the new system came into force on 16 May 1975.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] A shadow authority was again elected in 1995 ahead of the change to council areas which came into force on 1 April 1996.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The role of Lord Provost of Aberdeen is largely ceremonial.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] They chair full council meetings and act as the council's civic figurehead.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Political leadership is provided by the leader of the council.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen City Council currently comprises 45 councillors, who represent the city's wards, and is headed by the Lord Provost.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2012 council election there were 43 members of Aberdeen City Council.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2003 and 2007, the council was under the control of a Liberal Democrat and Conservative coalition, holding 23 of the 43 seats on the council.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2003 election, the council had been considered a Labour stronghold.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Two Liberal Democrat councillors became independents during this period due to personal controversies, while the four strong Conservative group split in August 2010, with two councillors forming the Scottish Conservative Group and two others the Aberdeen Conservative Group.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] After the May 2012 election, the control of the council shifted back to the Labour Party, supported in a coalition by three Conservative and three Independent councillors, giving the administration 23 seats.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The Labour/Conservative/Independent coalition continued after the 2017 election, but with a change in the balance of power within the coalition.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Labour were reduced to nine councillors (subsequently suspended from membership by the Scottish Labour Party for forming a coalition with the Conservatives), whilst the Conservatives had eleven councillors elected.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] These Conservative and suspended "Aberdeen Labour" councillors were joined in coalition by three Independent councillors, one of who had left the Liberal Democrats just days after the council election.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] In December 2019 a councillor elected as a Conservative became an Independent following his conviction for sexual assault.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] This led to the ruling coalition becoming a minority administration comprising only 22 of the 45 councillors.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2017 and 2021 the council had Co-Leaders Douglas Lumsden (Conservative) and Jenny Laing (“Aberdeen Labour”) as a result of the coalition agreement.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Following Douglas Lumsden's election to the Scottish Parliament in May 2021 Jenny Laing became sole Leader of the council.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] After the 2022 election the SNP and Liberal Democrats agreed to form a partnership to lead the Council for the next five years.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] At the Council's statutory meeting on 18 May 2022, SNP councillor David Cameron was elected Lord Provost and Liberal Democrat Councillor Steve Delaney was elected Depute Provost.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] SNP Group Leader Alex Nicoll and Liberal Democrat Group Leader Ian Yuill became Co-Leaders of the Council.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Effective April 2, 2026, Desmond Buchanan, Councillor for George Street/Harbour ward resigned.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The Returning Officer announced the By-Election will take place on Thursday, June 25th 2026.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Council meetings are held at Aberdeen Town House on Broad Street, which was built in 1874 and substantially extended in 1975, including a new council chamber.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The council's main offices are now in the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The council moved into the renovated former college building in 2011.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Before May 2007, councillors represented 43 single-member wards election on a first-past-the-post basis.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] On 3 May 2007, the single transferable vote system was used for the first time and multi-member wards were introduced, each ward electing three or four councillors.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] The Local Government Boundary Commission for Scotland completed its final recommendations for new wards for all the council areas of Scotland.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen is divided into 13 multi-member wards, electing a total of 45 councillors.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-city-council] This system was introduced as a result of the Local Governance (Scotland) Act 2004, and is designed to produce a form of proportional representation.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Port of Aberdeen is the largest port in Scotland (by berthage and area) and the busiest port via vessel visits in Scotland also.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] In 2023, the Port of Aberdeen opened South Harbour.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] This £420 million extension added 1.5km of deep water berthage to support cruise ships, cargo vessels and the Offshore wind sector.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Port of Aberdeen is the UK's oldest business, since 1136.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] A port has existed at Aberdeen since at least the 12th century, with the first recorded reference being from 1136, when King David I of Scotland permitted the Bishops of Aberdeen the right to charge a tithe on all vessels visiting the port.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Located on the estuary of the River Dee, the area initially comprised sandbanks and waterlogged marshes.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] At that time the river entered the area from the south west on a northerly course before turning eastwards towards the sea, featuring a series of channels and islets (known locally as 'inches').
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The channels were also fed by the Den Burn, a tributary of the Dee, which flowed from the north east.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The port was located on the northern most channel, immediately to the south of the town.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It is thought that these channels, sandbanks and islets changed position over time, as maps dating from 1661 and 1773 show noticeably different arrangements.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The area experienced a number of issues which could make navigation into the port difficult.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Coastal currents and northerly winds would often allow a sandbank to form at the mouth of the river, leaving a water depth of only a few feet.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The tidal area did not have any protection from easterly storms, and the channel leading to the town was shallow and obstructed.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The first known improvements to address these issues are recorded in a charter dating from 1281, which indicates that a bulwark ran southwards from the bottom of Shiprow.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It is thought that this may be the 'Old Pier' which appears on a 1773 plan of Aberdeen.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Later in 1339, records mention the 'quay of Aberdeen', which was repaired in 1453 and either repaired or rebuilt during 1484.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Shore Porters Society, one of the UK's oldest companies, was created to service the harbour in 1498.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It was established as a co-operative to provide transportation of goods to the centre of Aberdeen for a fixed rate.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The establishment of trade links with ports in Scandinavia and the Baltic states resulted in improvements being made at the port during the Tudor period.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] This included the installation of beacons at the entrance to the harbour, the clearance of obstructions from the channel and more repairs to the quayside in 1512 and 1526.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The work of 1526 specified cut stone, suggesting that the earlier quay may have been constructed from rough drystone masonry and timber.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The port's first cargo-handling crane was erected in 1582.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] During 1595 King James VI issued a charter to raise funding for improvements, with considerable work thereafter being undertaken, including repair of the bulwark, pier, shore and harbour.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] In an attempt to address the problem of the sandbank, a bulwark known as the 'South Pier' was constructed in 1609 on the south side of the harbour entrance.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It was formed from a drystone construction with timber stakes and positioned so that it would deflect the current of the river northwards, washing away the sandbank.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] However, the bank continued to cause problems, with water backing up and flowing over the quayside during floods.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] A project to extend the quay downstream commenced in 1623, finally being completed in 1659, after being delayed by the Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The extension of the quay allowed former tidal ground to the north to be reclaimed from the sea and put to agricultural use.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] A 1661 account and plan of Aberdeen by James Gordon, indicates that the quayside extended from Shiprow within the town, eastwards towards what was known as Futty, now the Queen's Links area between Waterloo Quay and Aberdeen Beach.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Near the mouth of the Dee, was Pockraw, a small fishing harbour, separate from the main port.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Gordon also recorded a weigh-house located near Shiprow, which had been built in the early 1630s.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Meanwhile, a fishing pier was constructed between 1611 and 1612 at Torry, Aberdeen's southern neighbour across the River Dee.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The layout of the modern harbour, as it largely remains today, can be traced back to around 1770, when planning for extensive development begun.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Civil engineer John Smeaton oversaw the construction of a breakwater (which became known as the North Pier) between 1775 and 1781 at Sandness (now known as Footdee or locally as *Fittie*).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The purpose of the breakwater was to prevent sand creating a bar at the harbour entrance and to direct the flow of deposits from the River Dee into the tidal current and away from the harbour.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The pier was constructed from rubble masonry with ashlar facing block and was 457 metres (500 yd; 1,499 ft) long, 9.1 metres (10.0 yd; 30 ft) wide and 4.6 metres (5.0 yd; 15 ft) high above the high-water level.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The works were overseen by the harbour's engineer John Gwyn and cost £16,000.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] In 1789, it was found necessary to narrow the navigation-channel to limit waves generated by the presence of the new north pier, with it being considered that the pier had been sited too far to the north.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Abercrombie Jetty (also known as the 'Catch Pier') was therefore constructed.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Civil engineer Thomas Telford recommended several improvements to the harbour in 1802.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] This included work to extend the North Pier to 610 metres (670 yd; 2,000 ft) to a point which terminated amongst rocks which had resulted in at least five shipwrecks.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Work to the pier was completed in 1816 at a cost of £16,000.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Improvements also involved the construction of a wet dock and spillway, and the diversion of the River Dee, all overseen by resident harbour engineer John Gibb.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] With the exception of the wet dock (of which only the quay-walls had been constructed), all these works were recorded as being complete by 1829.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] During the early 19th century, other major projects included the construction of wharfs along the length of Waterloo and Regent Quays and the creation of what at the time was called the South Breakwater, but now known as the Inner or Old South Breakwater.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It extended 243.8 metres (266.6 yd; 800 ft) from the south shore of the mouth of the River Dee and was completed between 1812 and 1815.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] With the exception of dredging, few improvements were undertaken between 1816 and 1829.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] More extensive works were undertaken between 1840 and 1846, under the direction of resident engineer James Abernethy.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] This included widening and deepening of the harbour, the dredging of sand-banks at the harbour entrance and removal of part of Abercromby's Jetty.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] During this period 303 metres (994 ft; 331 yd) of new quayside was constructed.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] At this point in time navigation into the harbour was difficult, particularly for long steamships, as it was necessary to make a turn of almost 90 degrees between Pockra jetty and the point of the 'inch' opposite.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] In 1833 Girdle Ness lighthouse was built on the headland just to the south of the harbour entrance.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] With the width of the entrance to the navigation channel restricted by the construction of the North Pier and South Breakwater, Abernethy considered it necessary to provide a navigational aid to assist vessels entering the harbour.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] As a solution, a pair of leading lights were constructed in Torry on the south shore of the River Dee.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] They were completed in 1842 and took the form of two cast iron tapering, octagonal-plan towers around 12 metres (39 ft).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Prior to the 19th century, Aberdeen's fishing industry was relatively small compared to other settlements in the north east of Scotland (such as Peterhead) and had focused largely on river and salmon fishing.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The traditional fishing fleets of Torry and Footdee also used line-fishing to catch white fish in the North Sea.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] In 1835, a herring fishing station was set up at the harbour, with Aberdeen's herring fleet bringing significant prosperity to the city.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] More efficient methods of fishing were introduced, with nets rather than lines being used to take advantage of herring shoals.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] A railway line to Aberdeen was opened in 1850, which allowed overnight fish trains to operate from the city to Billingsgate Fish Market in London.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] One of the most important changes during the harbour's history took place between 1843 and 1848, when the docks onto which the town's quaysides fronted were finally enclosed to create the Victoria Dock, a wet-dock of 13.8 hectares (34 acres).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Replacing Wellington Quay and Lime Quay, the scheme was based on Telford's original proposals and were developed by James Abernethy with help from engineers James Walker and Alexander Gibb.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The dock was divided into two parts, separated by the Regent swinging bridge.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] There was a larger dock to the east and smaller dock to the west, the latter corresponding with what is now known as the Upper Dock.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Victoria Dock had a depth of 4.9 metres (16 ft) and could accommodate 300 vessels.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It featured two iron entrance-lock gates, 18 metres (60 ft) and 21 metres (70 ft) wide, one for vessels and the other operating as a tide gate.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The northern quayside was named Waterloo Quay and the southern named Provost Blaikies Quay.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] During the period, the River Dee followed a course which corresponds with the modern-day Albert Basin, which was yet to be constructed.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Plans to divert the River Dee to its current route were agreed in 1868, allowing for the creation of the Albert Basin between 1869 and 1872, with Commercial Road to the formed to the north and Albert Quay to the south.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The work resulted in the demolition of much of Old Torry on the south side of the river, the separate burgh being incorporated into the City of Aberdeen during 1891.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Albert Basin became the centre of the port's fishing industry, being home from 1889 to a covered fish market located at Commercial Quay which could accommodate several hundred vessels.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Steam trawlers were introduced to the Aberdeen fishing fleet in 1882, the first being converted Tyneside-built tugboat the *Toiler.* Steam powered vessels were larger and faster than sailing ships and by 1912 over 230 steam trawlers were based in Aberdeen.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Due to the higher cost of steam trawlers, fishing became increasingly more commercialised, with boats being operated by companies who paid their crews a wage, rather than family businesses who would share the value of the catch with their crew.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] To support the fishing industry several related industries prospered in the city, including the fish market, fish processing and ship building.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The fish processing industry was dominated by women who cured, gutted and packed fish, typically in teams of three, with one team for each boat.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] A dry dock for the repair and maintenance of steamships was opened in January 1885 at the east end of the Albert Basin.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Known as Pacific Wharf, the dry dock operated until 1915.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It was demolished between 1924 and 1927 to allow for an extension to the fish market.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The North Pier was extended for a third and final time between 1874 and 1877, under the **Aberdeen Harbour Act 1868** (31 & 32 Vict. c. cxxxviii) which authorise wider improvement works.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] A further 152.3 metres (500 ft; 166.6 yd) was added using concrete, resulting in its current length of 792.7 metres (2,601 ft; 866.9 yd).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Matthews Quay was constructed in 1885 and named after Aberdeen Lord Provost James Matthews, who was also a prominent architect in the city.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The early 20th century saw the expansion of quaysides on the southern shores of the River Dee, with River Dee Dock No.1 and Maitlands Quay being constructed to the west of Torry Harbour between 1909 and 1915.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] This coincided with the development of Torry which saw new streets, a school and church being built and later the Torry Marine Laboratory, shipbuilding yards and sawmills.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] On 1 July 1909, crowds gathered to watch escape artist Harry Houdini perform an escape from the harbour waters whilst he was chained and handcuffed.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Annual Reports of the Fishery Board for Scotland provide an insight into fishing in Aberdeen in the years before the First World War.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] For example, the report for 1902 is very enthusiastic: "The marvellous succss of the trawling industry is the principal point of interest.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Everything connected with it has made substantial increase since last year.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] 286 additional fishermen have been employed; the vessels trawling from the port have increased from 186 to 281...".
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] At that time, neither the trawlers nore their crews were included in the Board's statistics.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] This changed in 1910, resulting in the abrupt differences to be seen in the charts below.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] By this point in time the report states that fishing boats from Aberdeen were fishing off Shetland, Orkney North Western Grounds, St.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Kilda, Flannan Islands, Barrahead, West Coast of Ireland, Iceland and Faroe and in the North Sea in latitudes 56° to 61°.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Aberdeen's last steam trawlers stopped fishing in the 1950s as they were replaced by motor powered boats which had become more affordable and efficient.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] By the 1960s, Aberdeen was established as the primary whitefish port in Scotland and after Hull and Grimsby one of the main trawler ports in the UK.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Aberdeen fleet consisted of a mixture of middle-distance trawlers embarking on sixteen-day trips to the seas around the Faroe Islands and smaller vessels known as Aberdeen scratchers, which operated in the North Sea and off the west coast of Scotland.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The fleet also comprised around thirty larger great-line boats, which would typically be at sea for up to 28 days and fished in deeper waters, predominately for halibut.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Although several local owners invested in new stern trawlers, by the late 1960s, Aberdeen was facing economic decline with an ageing fishing fleet rapidly reducing in size and the ship building industry also declining.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] In 1978 Aberdeen was still the main Scottish port for white-fish processing, with approximately 2,500 full-time employees working in the sector.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] However, most of the fish landed in Aberdeen was from seine net boats sailing from ports in Fife and north-east Scotland rather than the Aberdeen fleet.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Aberdeen's economic prospects improved when oil and natural gas were discovered in the North Sea, however the significance of this to Aberdeen was not apparent until the discovery by BP of the Forties field in October 1970 and the East Shetland Basin discovery by Shell in July 1971.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] In 1973, Shell became the first oil company to enter a partnership with the harbour to create an oil and gas supply base at Maitlands Quay on the River Dee.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The redevelopment saw the remainder of Old Torry demolished, with only a few houses left and none dating from earlier than the 19th century.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The late 1960s and early 1970s saw investment from central government to allow the reconstruction of Mearns Quay, 180 metres (600 ft) of Commercial Quay and part of the fish-market.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Victoria Dock was redeveloped and the tide locks at Waterloo Quay were removed in 1975, resulting in the whole harbour again becoming tidal, with dredging occurring as necessary to maintain the required depths.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Other offshore supply bases were established and the harbour went through a period of significant redevelopment to become the primary port in Europe to serve the offshore oil and gas industry.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] In 1984, Mearns Quay was extended westwards into the River Dee Dock through the use of steel sheet piling.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] During the 1990s, the harbour was host to the Cutty Sark Tall Ships Race on two occasions.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The first visit, during 1991 saw more than 310,000 people visited the city to see the dozens of sailing ships taking part in the race.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The event included a fire works display launched from the North Pier.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The second visit of the race during 1997 saw attracted 558,000 visitors.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] As a result of a declining fishing industry in Aberdeen, market sales of fish ended in the mid-1990s.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The fish market at Commercial Quay was demolished between 2006 and 2007, 118 years after the first covered market was established at the harbour.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] By 2015, it was estimated that the harbour generated approximately £1.5 billion (gross value added) and 12,260 jobs for the Scottish economy.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] This included £1.4 billion (GVA) and 9,565 jobs for the Aberdeen City and Aberdeenshire economies.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] A £36m project to infill the River Dee Dock and create four new berths along the River Dee was completed in 2016.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] In May 2017, construction started on a new harbour at Nigg Bay to the south of the existing harbour.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The £350 million project is the largest marine infrastructure project in the UK and when complete will be the largest port in terms of available berths in Scotland, capable of accommodating vessels up to 300m in length.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Four new quays are under construction, the 300m-long Balmoral Quay, the 400m-long Dunnottar Quay, the 175m-long Crathes Quay and the 540m-long Castlegate Quay.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The new harbour is expected to create an additional 7,000 jobs and add £1 billion annually to the economy by 2035.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] In May 2022, the harbour was rebranded from Aberdeen Harbour to Port of Aberdeen.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The new name encompasses both the new south harbour as well as the original harbour which since the development of the new harbour has sometimes been known as the *north harbour*.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The rebranding was undertaken to avoid confusion between the two parts of the harbour and to reflect the commercial nature of the port.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Aberdeen had a significant shipbuilding industry for over 200 years, with over 3,000 ships being built at shipyards within the port between 1790 and 1990.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Established in 1790, Alexander Hall and Sons was known for building sailing ships such as *Scottish Maid* and designed the 'Aberdeen' or 'clipper' bow in 1839.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It also built steam ships, one of the most famous being the *Jho Sho Maru* which was built for the Imperial Japanese Navy in the 1860s.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The yard failed to modernise and was acquired by Aberdeen-based Hall, Russell & Company in 1957.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Walter Hood & Co. shipyard opened in 1839 and was located adjacent to Pocra jetty, east of the Hall Russell yard.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It is considered to have produced some of the finest sailing ships built in Aberdeen, including the clipper *Thermopylae*, which was built for the Aberdeen Line and launched in 1868.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The yard never manufactured engines and with propeller-driven vessels becoming increasingly popular the yard became unable to compete, leading to a merger with Alexander Hall and Sons in 1871.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The first Duthie Shipyard was opened in 1816 by William Duthie.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It mainly predominately built brigantines and schooners but also undertook repair work.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] In 1839 it was renamed Alexander Duthie & Co. and began building clipper bow vessels, both for local and international customers.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] In 1861, the yard became John Duthie, Sons & Co. and throughout the 1860s continued to produce vessels constructed from timber, despite competitors developing use of composite designs and iron.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The yard's first iron vessel was launched in 1869 and by the 1880s the yard predominately built trawlers.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It closed in 1907 with the premises taken over by Hall Russell.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Two other yard operated by the Duthie family existed.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] William Duthie Junior operated a yard from the inches opposite Footdee from 1855 to 1870.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] John Duthie Torry Shipbuilding Co. was located in Torry between 1904 and 1925.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] John Lewis & Sons was established in 1907, initially producing and repairing marine engines at Maitlands Quay area in Torry.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] With the First World War generating demand, it built its first vessel in 1917, going on to specialise in cargo and fishing vessels.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It constructed the last Aberdeen-built sailing ship, the sail-training schooner *Malcolm Miller*, in 1967.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The yard was purchased by Wood Group in 1972 and its activities moved towards ship repair.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Hall, Russell & Company was established in 1864.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It built a wide range of fishing boats, cargo steamers and trawlers.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] During the First World War, the yard constructed minesweeper trawlers and during the Second World War contributed to the war effort by producing *Flower-*class corvettes, frigates and other naval vessels.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Post-war, Hall Russell constructed trawlers and cargo ships, including the freighter *Thameshaven* in 1971, which was Aberdeen's largest ever vessel with a deadweight of 10,500 tonnes.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] In 1977, the yard was nationalised and became part of the state-owned British Shipbuilders.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It built several offshore patrol vessels and torpedo recovery vessels for the British Ministry of Defence.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It was privatised in 1986 and despite traditionally building fishing and cargo vessels, was classed as a naval shipbuilder.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] This hindered the ability to obtain contracts in the merchant vessel market, resulting in a downturn in work.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The yard was acquired by A&P Appledore in 1989 but business did not improve.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The last vessel to be built at the yard and in Aberdeen was cargo-liner RMS *St Helena* which was completed in 1990, bring over 200 years of shipbuilding in Aberdeen to an end.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The yard carried out repair work until its closure in 1992.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The site was redeveloped to create the Telford Dock, which provided five new deep-water berths, a jetty, two transit sheds and 26,000sqm of heavy-duty paved open storage.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The dock's quays were each named after Aberdeen's shipbuilders, except for the Clipper Quay which relates to the bow design invented in the city.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Port of Aberdeen has six docks, each with several quays and berths as described below.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] A dry dock is located between Russells Quay and Pocra Quay.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Marine House, located at Blakies Quay, is home to Aberdeen Coastguard Operations Centre (CGOC), part of Her Majesty's Coastguard and in turn the Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It is one of ten CGOC located around the United Kingdom and covers the east coast of Scotland between the inner Moray Firth to the north and outer Firth of Forth to the south.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It is responsible for the mobilisation, organisation and tasking of adequate resources to respond to persons in distress in the air, at sea, in tidal waters or at risk of injury or death on the sea cliffs and shoreline within its area.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] HM Coastguard's Aberdeen Coastguard Rescue Team is also based at Marine House and covers a 25 miles (40 km) stretch of coastline to the north and south of Aberdeen.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The MCA's Aberdeen Marine and Fishing Survey Office is also located in Marine House.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Royal National Lifeboat Institution's (RNLI) Aberdeen Lifeboat Station is located at the entrance to the Victoria Dock.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The station operates one Severn-class all-weather lifeboat (named *Bon Accord*) and one D-class inshore lifeboat (*James Bissett Simpson).* A station was first established in 1802 by the Harbour Commissioners before being transferred to the RNLI in 1925.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The current lifeboat station was constructed in 1997, providing indoor space for the D-class lifeboat and improved crew facilities.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Port operations are controlled from the Marine Operations Centre located at the base of the North Pier.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The building was completed in 2006 at a cost of £4.5 million.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It was designed by SMC Parr Architects and is reminiscent of a traditional lighthouse, utilising precast concrete with white aggregate as well as faceted curtain wall glazing.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Its prominent location at the mouth of the River Dee allows Vessel Traffic Services (VTS) staff to have an overview of the various docks and harbour entrance.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The facility also features ship's bridge simulator used in training.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] VTS controls all shipping movements within the harbour and within a two-mile radius of the head of the North Pier.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Oilfield services provider Petrofac operates a training centre with water access onto the River Dee.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The centre operates a fleet of Fast Rescue Craft and survival craft and provides training in their operation.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Waterloo Mult- Modal Terminal is located immediately to the north of Waterloo Quay and provides a connection to the national rail network.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The terminal is built on the site of the former Aberdeen Waterloo railway station which operated for passengers between 1856 and 1867 and freight until the 1960s when the station was demolished.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Port of Aberdeen is the main commercial port in north east Scotland, predominately serving the offshore oil and gas industry.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It also handles a variety of bulk, forest products, grains and mineral cargoes.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Aberdeen is principal port servicing the UK North Sea offshore oil and gas industry.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It handles a wide range of ships supporting the industry including platform supply vessels, dive support vessels, anchor handling tugs, survey vessels and emergency response vessels.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] By 2015, such vessels accounted for between 65% and 75% of the marine traffic at the harbour.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Aberdeen is the mainland terminus for passenger and freight ferry routes to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The services are run by NorthLink Ferries which operates two passenger vessels, MV *Hjaltland* and MV *Hrossey*, both of which entered service in 2002.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The passenger terminal is located at Jamieson's Quay and there are nightly sailings to Shetland, with one vessel sailing from Aberdeen to Lerwick while the other ship sails in the opposite direction.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] One ship will sail directly whilst the other stops at Kirkwall in Orkney.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] NorthLink also operates two freight ferries, MV *Hildasay* and MV *Helliar*, which provide a daily service to the islands carrying a wide range of cargo including vehicles, live-stock and fish, temperature-controlled foodstuffs, shipping containers, and out-sized loads.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The freight ferries berth at ro-ro ramps located at Jamiesons Quay and Matthew's Quay North.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Port of Aberdeen is a trust port, owned and operated by **Aberdeen Harbour Board**.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The board is an independent statutory body established by the **Aberdeen Harbour Order Confirmation Act 1960** (9 & 10 Eliz.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] 2. c. i), and amended by the **Aberdeen Harbour Order Confirmation Act 1987** (c. xxi).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The board is responsible for the port's administration, maintenance and improvement.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Unlike a privately owned port, there are no shareholders who require a dividend and all profits made from operations are reinvested into the port.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The current chief executive is Bob Sanguinetti and chairperson is Alistair Mackenzie.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Aberdeen Harbour Board replaced the Aberdeen Harbour Commission, which was formed in 1843 and was revised through several acts of Parliament during the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Aberdeen Harbour Board are based in offices at 15-16 Regent Quay.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The building designed by Scottish architect Alexander Marshall Mackenzie was built between 1883 and 1885.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Purpose-built for the harbour board, it signified the prosperity that the harbour was experiencing at the end of the nineteenth century.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It is a four-storey, eight-bay block featuring a clock tower with a domed roof.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It is constructed from ashlar grey granite to the principal elevations and tower, with coursed pink granite to the rear.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] HMS *Clyde* was a Royal Naval Reserve training ship which was moored in the Upper Dock during the 19th century.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The vessel was replaced in 1904 by a 1081-ton man o' war also named HMS *Clyde* (previously HMS *Wild Swan*).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It was connected to the quayside by a floating gangway and was open to the public on Sunday mornings.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] She was later relocated to Albert Quay and decommissioned around 1911.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] In 1967, Aberdeen University Royal Naval Unit (URNU) was established at the harbour.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] From 1991 until its relocation to Edinburgh in 2012, the unit operated HMS *Archer* (P264), an *Archer-*class patrol vessel.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] HMS *Diamond* (D34), a Type-45 destroyer of the Royal Navy commissioned in 2011 is affiliated with Aberdeen City.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The vessel has visited Aberdeen Harbour during 2011, November 2015 and August 2018.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] During such visits the vessel has been open to the public and her crew has taken part in community and civic events.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Naval vessels occasionally dock in Aberdeen whilst taking part in NATO's Exercise Joint Warrior which takes place in the seas around Scotland.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The River Dee, including the stretch within the harbour boundaries, is designated as a Special Area of Conservation under the European Union's Habitats Directive (92/43/EEC), because of its populations of freshwater pearl mussel, Atlantic salmon and otter.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The harbour and Aberdeen Bay is frequented by a variety of marine mammals, including resident populations of harbour porpoise, bottlenose dolphin, grey seal and harbour seal as well as seasonal populations of minke whale.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The former Navigation Control Centre (known as 'The Roundhouse', despite being an octagon, or as the 'Pilots House') is located at Pocra Quay.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It is thought that it was constructed between 1797 and 1798, with the Shoremaster's accounts for that period indicating over £225 was spent constructing a 'new house' on the North Pier.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Ten guineas were also recorded as being spent on a telescope for the 'Lookout House' on the North Pier.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The building appears on a map of Footdee from 1803 and is the village's oldest.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The building's purpose was to guide vessels to the harbour, this originally being carried out by the harbour pilots using megaphone from a platform forming part of the roof of the original two-storey structure, or by a series of wicker balls attached to a mast rising from the platform.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The building was extended in 1966 when the control tower section was added and in 1974 a radar system was introduced.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It was updated again in 1986, when Queen Elizabeth II unveiled a plaque, commemorating '850 years of Harbour History'.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The Roundhouse's role was replaced by the Marine Operations Centre in 2006, with the harbour board retaining ownership of the building and leasing it out as office space.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The building was category C listed in July 2007.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It is described by Historic Environment Scotland as a rare survivor of its type, notable for its unusual octagonal form and relatively early construction date.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Scarty's Monument is a brick obelisk located at Pocra Quay, named after a harbour pilot who kept watch during poor weather from the North Pier in the mid 19th century.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Rather than being an actual monument, it is in fact a ventilator shaft for a disused sewer that discharged into the harbour navigation channel.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] 6 Regent Road (also known as United House) located between the Victoria and Albert Docks, is an example of a late 19th century warehouse associated with the harbour.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Once numerous around the harbour, few such warehouses now survive.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Constructed from granite with a slate roof, it is three-storeys in height and features a distinctive M-shaped gable.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] A pair of public works drainage buildings dating from 1906 are situated on Mearns Quay and Torry Quay, on opposite sides of the River Dee.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] The two polished grey granite ashlar buildings are described by Historic Environment Scotland as being of some quality with fine Classical architectural detailing and cast-iron rainwater goods.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] It is also noted that functional buildings of this type with such attention to detail are rare and that they contribute significantly to the built environment of the harbour.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] They were category C listed in July 2007.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Located at Pocra Quay adjacent to the Roundhouse, the Abercrombie Jetty (also known as the 'Catch Pier') was constructed in 1789 as part of wider harbour improvements.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Its purpose was to limit waves generated by the new north pier from the entering the navigation channel.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Its namesake was the Provost of the time, John Abercrombie (1729–1820).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] Once finished the jetty itself proved to be a significant danger to navigation, and therefore was largely removed, with only a small part remaining.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/aberdeen-harbour] A carved stone commemorating Abercrombie exists at the base of the structure.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The **Admiralty** was a department of the Kingdom of Great Britain and from 1801 of the Government of the United Kingdom that was responsible for the command of the Royal Navy.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Historically, its titular head was the Lord High Admiral – one of the Great Officers of State.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] For much of its history, from the early 18th century until its abolition, the role of the Lord High Admiral was almost invariably put "in commission" and exercised by the Lords Commissioner of the Admiralty, who sat on the governing Board of Admiralty, rather than by a single person.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Admiralty was replaced by the Admiralty Board in 1964, as part of the reforms that created the Ministry of Defence and its Navy Department (later Navy Command).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Admiralty was among the most important departments of the British Government, because of the Royal Navy's role in the expansion and maintenance of the English overseas possessions in the 17th century, the British Empire in the 18th century, and subsequently.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The modern Admiralty Board, to which the functions of the Admiralty were transferred in 1964, is a committee of the tri-service Defence Council of the United Kingdom.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] This Admiralty Board meets only twice a year, and the day-to-day running of the Royal Navy is controlled by a Navy Board (not to be confused with the historic Navy Board).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] It is common for the various authorities now in charge of the Royal Navy to be referred to as simply 'The Admiralty'.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Since 1964, the title of Lord High Admiral of the United Kingdom has been vested in the monarch; the title was awarded to Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh by Queen Elizabeth II on his 90th birthday in 2011 and remained with him until his death in 2021.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] There also continues to be a Vice-Admiral of the United Kingdom and a Rear-Admiral of the United Kingdom, both of which are honorary offices.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The office of Admiral of England (later Lord Admiral, and later Lord High Admiral) was created around 1400; there had previously been Admirals of the northern and western seas.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] King Henry VIII established the Council of the Marine—later to become the Navy Board—in 1546, to oversee administrative affairs of the naval service.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Operational control of the Royal Navy remained the responsibility of the Lord High Admiral, who was one of the nine Great Officers of State.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] This management approach would continue in force in the Royal Navy until 1832.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] King Charles I put the office of Lord High Admiral into commission in 1628, and control of the Royal Navy passed to a committee in the form of the Board of Admiralty.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The office of Lord High Admiral passed a number of times in and out of commission until 1709, after which the office was almost permanently in commission (the last Lord High Admiral being the future King William IV in the early 19th century).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] These principal officers came to be known as the Navy Board responsible for 'civil administration' of the navy, from 1546 to 1832.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] This structure of administering the navy lasted for 285 years, however, the supply system was often inefficient and corrupt its deficiencies were due as much to its limitations of the times they operated in.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The various functions within the Admiralty were not coordinated effectively and lacked inter-dependency with each other, with the result that in 1832, Sir James Graham abolished the Navy Board and merged its functions within those of the Board of Admiralty.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] At the time this had distinct advantages; however, it failed to retain the principle of distinctions between the Admiralty and supply, and a lot of bureaucracy followed with the merger.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] In 1860 saw big growth in the development of technical crafts, the expansion of more admiralty branches that really began with age of steam that would have an enormous influence on the navy and naval thought.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Between 1860 and 1908, there was no real study of strategy and of staff work conducted within the naval service; it was practically ignored.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] All the Navy's talent flowed to the great technical universities.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] This school of thought for the next 50 years was exclusively technically based.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The first serious attempt to introduce a sole management body to administer the naval service manifested itself in the creation of the Admiralty Navy War Council in 1909.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Following this, a new advisory body called the Admiralty War Staff was then instituted in 1912, headed by the Chief of the War Staff who was responsible for administering three new sub-divisions responsible for operations, intelligence and mobilisation.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The new War Staff had hardly found its feet and it continually struggled with the opposition to its existence by senior officers they were categorically opposed to a staff.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The deficiencies of the system within this government department could be seen in the conduct of the Dardanelles campaign.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] There were no mechanisms in place to answer the big strategic questions.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Sir John Jellicoe came to the Admiralty in 1916.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] He reorganised the war staff as following: Chief of War Staff, Operations, Intelligence, Signal Section, Mobilisation, Trade.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] It was not until 1917 that the admiralty department was again properly reorganised and began to function as a professional military staff.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] In May 1917, the term "Admiralty War Staff" was renamed and that department and its functional role were superseded by a new "Admiralty Naval Staff"; in addition, the newly created office of Chief of the Naval Staff was merged in the office of the First Sea Lord.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Also appointed was a new post, that of Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff, and an Assistant Chief of the Naval Staff; all were given seats on the Board of Admiralty.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] This for the first time gave the naval staff direct representation on the board; the presence of three senior naval senior members on the board ensured the necessary authority to carry through any operation of war.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Deputy Chief of Naval Staff would direct all operations and movements of the fleet, while the Assistant Chief of Naval Staff would be responsible for mercantile movements and anti-submarine operations.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The office of Controller would be re-established to deal with all questions relating to supply; on 6 September 1917, a Deputy First Sea Lord, was added to the Board who would administer operations abroad and deal with questions of foreign policy.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] In October 1917, the development of the staff was carried one step further by the creation of two sub-committees of the Board—the Operations Committee and the Maintenance Committee.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The First Lord of the Admiralty was chairman of both committees, and the Operations Committee consisted of the First Sea Lord and Chief of Naval Staff, the Deputy First Sea Lord, Assistant Chief of Naval Staff, and Fifth Sea Lord.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Full operational control of the Royal Navy was finally handed over to the Chief of Naval Staff (CNS) by an order in Council, effective October 1917, under which he became responsible for the issuing of orders affecting all war operations directly to the fleet.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] It also empowered the CNS to issue orders in their own name, as opposed to them previously being issued by the Permanent Secretary of the Admiralty in the name of the Board.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] In 1964, the Admiralty—along with the War Office and the Air Ministry—were abolished as separate departments of state, and placed under one single new Ministry of Defence.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Within the expanded Ministry of Defence are the new Admiralty Board which has a separate Navy Board responsible for the day-to-day running of the Royal Navy, the Army Board and the Air Force Board, each headed by the Secretary of State for Defence.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] In order to deliver this the Naval Staff was organised into specialist Divisions and Sections.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] When the Admiralty unified with the Ministry of Defence in 1964 they were re designated as Directorates of the Naval Staff.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Admiralty Departments, which provides the men, ships, aircraft and supplies to carry out the approved policy.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The departments are superintended by the various offices of the Sea Lords.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Department of the Permanent Secretary which was the general co-ordinating agency, regulating naval finance, providing advice on policy, conducing all correspondence on behalf of the Board and maintaining admiralty records.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Its primary component to deliver this is the Admiralty Secretariat, sections of the Secretariat (other than those which provide Common Services) were known as Branches.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Board of Admiralty consisted of a number of Lords Commissioners of the Admiralty.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Lords Commissioners were always a mixture of admirals, known as Naval Lords or Sea Lords and Civil Lords, normally politicians.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The quorum of the Board was two commissioners and a secretary.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The president of the Board was known as the First Lord of the Admiralty, who was a member of the Cabinet.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] After 1806, the First Lord of the Admiralty was always a civilian, while the professional head of the navy came to be (and is still today) known as the First Sea Lord.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Lords Commissioners of the Admiralty were the members of The Board of Admiralty, which exercised the office of Lord High Admiral when it was not vested in a single person.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The commissioners were a mixture of politicians without naval experience and professional naval officers, the proportion of naval officers generally increasing over time.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The First Sea Lord and Chief of Naval Staff was the Chief Naval Adviser on the Board of Admiralty to the First Lord and superintended the offices of the sea lords and the admiralty naval staff.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Navy Board was an independent board from 1546 until 1628 when it became subordinate to, yet autonomous of the Board of Admiralty until 1832.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Its principal commissioners of the Navy advised the board in relation to civil administration of the naval affairs.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Navy Board was based at the Navy Office.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Office of the Additional Civil Lord of the Admiralty.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Office of the Parliamentary and Financial Secretary to the Admiralty.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] It evolved from *Admiralty Navy War Council, (1909–1912) which in turn became the Admiralty War Staff, (1912–1917) before finally becoming the Admiralty Naval Staff in 1917.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] It was the former senior command, operational planning, policy and strategy department within the British Admiralty.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Office of the Vice Chief of the Naval Staff.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] Offices of the Assistant Chiefs of the Naval Staff.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Secretary's Department consisted of members of the civil service it was directed and controlled by a senior civil servant Permanent Secretary to the Board of Admiralty he was not a Lord Commissioner of the Admiralty, he functioned as a member of the board, and attended all of its meetings.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/admiralty-united-kingdom] In some cases, the term *admiralty* is used in a wider sense, as meaning *sea power* or *rule over the seas*, rather than in strict reference to the institution exercising such power.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] The **Age of Sail** is the period in European history from the mid-15th or 16th century to, at the latest, the mid-19th century, in which the dominance of sailing ships in global trade and warfare culminated.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] Marked by the introduction of naval artillery, the Age of Sail ultimately reached its highest extent at the advent of steam power.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] Enabled by the advances of the related age of navigation, it is identified as a distinctive element of the early modern period and the Age of Discovery.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] Like most periodic eras, defining the age is inexact and serves only as a general description.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] The term is used differently for warships and merchant vessels.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] By the 14th century naval artillery was employed in Europe, documented at the Battle of Arnemuiden (1338).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] The 15th century saw the Iberian naval ventures all the way along the African Atlantic coast and across the Atlantic Ocean, starting the Age of Discovery.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] For warships, the age of sail runs roughly from the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, the last significant engagement in which oar-propelled galleys played a major role, to the development of steam-powered warships.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] The period between the mid-19th century to the early 20th century, when sailing vessels reached their peak of size and complexity (e.g. clippers and windjammers), is sometimes referred to as the "Golden Age of Sail".
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] The second sea-going steamboat was Richard Wright's first steamboat *Experiment*, an ex-French lugger; she steamed from Leeds to Yarmouth in July 1813.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] The first iron steamship to go to sea was the 116-ton *Aaron Manby*, built in 1821 by Aaron Manby at the Horseley Ironworks, and became the first iron-built vessel to put to sea when she crossed the English Channel in 1822, arriving in Paris on 22 June.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] She carried passengers and freight to Paris in 1822 at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] The first purpose-built steam battleship was the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] Multiple steam battleships saw action during the Crimean War, especially the Allied (British, French and Ottoman) fleet Bombardment of Sevastopol as part of the Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855).
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] The first ironclad battleship, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in November 1859.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] In the March 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads, the ironclad CSS *Virginia* fought USS *Monitor*, making this the first fight between ironclads.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] The Suez Canal in the Middle East, which opened in 1869, was more practical for steamships than for sailing ships, achieving a much shorter European-Asian sea route, which coincided with more fuel-efficient steamships, starting with *Agamemnon* in 1865.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] HMS *Devastation*, the first class of ocean-going battleships that did not carry sails, was commissioned in 1871.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] Sailing ships continued to be an economical way to transport bulk cargo on long voyages into the 1920s and 1930s, though steamships soon pushed them out of those trades as well.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] Sailing ships do not require fuel or complex engines to be powered; thus they tended to be more independent from sophisticated dedicated support bases on land.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] Crucially though, steam-powered ships held a speed advantage and were rarely hindered by adverse winds, freeing steam-powered vessels from the necessity of following trade winds.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] As a result, cargo and supplies could reach a foreign port in a fraction of the time it took a sailing ship.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] Sailing vessels were pushed into narrower and narrower economic niches and gradually disappeared from commercial trade.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] Today, sailing vessels are only economically viable for small-scale coastal fishing, along with recreational uses such as yachting and passenger sail excursion ships.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] In recent decades, the commercial shipping industry has been reviving interest in wind assisted ships as a way to conserve fuel in the interest of sustainability.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] A **New Age of Sail** has been predicted by some experts to occur by 2030, driven by a revolution in energy technology and a desire to reduce carbon emissions from maritime shipping through wind-assisted propulsion.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/age-of-sail] The book *Trade Winds: A Voyage to a Sustainable Future for Shipping* discusses the potential of a return to wind propulsion through the firsthand experiences of Christiaan De Beukelaer, who spent five months aboard a sailing cargo ship in 2020.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] Alexander Hall (1760–1849) was born in Auchterless, moved to Aberdeen in 1783 and took over his father-in-law’s shipbuilding business Cochar and Gibbon in 1790 to found Alexander Hall and Company.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] The first ships he built were wooden sailing vessels.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] A schooner built in 1839, The *Scottish Maid*, was the first to use the "Aberdeen bow", which was designed to improve speed and performance.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] When he died in 1849, Alexander Hall left the shipyard to his sons James and William.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] William took charge of ship design and James ran the business.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] They built many famous clippers, including *Torrington* in 1845 and *Stornoway* in 1850, used on the opium and tea routes.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] One ship later developed was the *Ihoshu Maru*, a barque-rigged steamship, built in the 1860s for the Imperial Japanese Navy.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] This vessel carried a belt of iron armour plating at the waterline together with eight 64 pounder and two 100 pounder guns.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] James suffered a fatal heart attack when a fire broke out in the yard during the ship's construction.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] Before the end of the 1870s, the firm had built 290 sailing ships.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] The firm built steamships as well as sailing ships.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] It built its first marine steam engine in 1887, and installed it in the launch *Petrel*.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] It built its first trawler, *Maggie Walker*, in 1888, followed by more trawlers, coasters, tugs and dredgers.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] In World War II Hall built 26 steam tugs, a large number being supplied to the Admiralty.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] The firm became deeply involved with the welfare of its employees, starting a medical fund in 1846 which took care of sick pay, medical attention and medication, and met funeral expenses.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] Failure to modernise and adapt after the war caused a decline in Hall's fortunes and in 1957 Hall, Russell & Company took over the company.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] Hall, Russell became part of British Shipbuilders in 1977.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] In the latter years the yard focused on ship repair work.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] A&P Appledore bought Alexander Hall's former shipyard.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] It closed in 1992 and was replaced by River Dee Ship Repairers.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/alexander-hall-and-sons] Today the site is part of Telford Dock and now has a modern drydock belonging to Dales Marine Services Limited (founded 1987), a ship repair and maintenance facility.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/asia-1818-ship] In 1813 the EIC had lost its monopoly on the trade between India and Britain.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/asia-1818-ship] British ships were then free to sail to India or the Indian Ocean under a license from the EIC.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/asia-1818-ship] *Asia* first appeared in *Lloyd's Register* (*LR*) in 1820 with I.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/asia-1818-ship] Morris, master, McInnis, owner, and trade London-Bombay.
[src:alexander-hall-and-sons/asia-1818-ship] On 7 July 1819, *Asia*, Morrice, master, sailed from Deal on 7 July 1819, bound for Bombay, and arrived back at Gravesend on 23 June 1820.
